##Dr. Xiehe, Wuhan: I've never worn such an expensive protective suit

NVHAIBIEPA

Function introduction, for Chinese women's safety, to provide professional solutions.

Hi, I'm Tian Jing.

During SARS in 2003, Chai Jing interviewed frontline medical staff: "What Protection Do you have? "? "

The doctor's answer at the time was: "We rely on mental protection. "

Seventeen years later, with another outbreak, medical resources are still scarce.

Our Wuhan Girl Chen has been insisting on volunteering at the front line these days.

She got her friends to pay for it. While helping to coordinate medical donations, he took the risk of walking out the door and sending face masks, goggles and protective clothing to front-line doctors.
Chen remembered that a male doctor kept saying thank you when he took over 30 goggles in her hands. After turning and walking a few steps, she suddenly turned around and bowed to her at a 90 degree angle.

Another doctor, after hearing her offer to send her a suit with a friend, smiled sheepishly like her brother next door: I've never worn a suit like this!

The other two doctors she had contact with were still in the hospital, suffering from infections due to a lack of medical supplies and a heavy workload.

One of the female doctors is doing a C.T. on a possible patient. At the beginning of their department only a protective clothing, people can only be sterilized after the rotation wear. After working 36 hours straight, she developed a high fever and was finally diagnosed.

These only have the first-line medical worker of brief intersection, all let Chen Chen feel distressed and broken-hearted. She records their stories, and she records this history.

Some people say, "there are no heroes who fall from the sky, only mortals who rise up. ". "

Every mortal who stands up for himself should be remembered as long as we can, a little longer. So that in a few decades, a hundred years, it won't be a lost legend.

By Chen Chen
Editor: Jing Tian
He smiled sheepishly. I've never worn a suit like this before
On January 23, the day the city was shut down in Wuhan, a group of my mother's friends asked me if I had any surgical masks, and Dr. Lin of the Pediatric Department of Concord Hospital was in urgent need.

I'm surprised. It's a top-three hospital. Why would they be short of supplies? And by the way, are you sure it was Dr. Lim?

She sent me a screenshot of Dr. Lin's chat.

At that time, I just had a box of Shenzhen friends sent medical surgical masks. Dr. Lim offered to come and get it himself.

I met him that afternoon at 2:30 by the second ring road in Hankou.

The smog that day. In Wuhan in the depth of winter, the leaves on the street fell to the ground. The streets are empty.

"The empty city of Wuhan" by Lin Chen, an empty Wuhan Shopping Street / Vlog Blogger

I handed him 200 masks and asked him, why don't you have any protection?

They're not a first line department, so an N95 lasts three days, with a surgical mask inside, and they only change the surgical mask inside, not the N95, he said.

He wore a mask and spoke slowly, with resignation and exhaustion in his voice.

My nose gets sore all of a sudden.

I said, I have taken the child to see you before, you must take care.

We shook hands heavily.

As he turned to leave, I had a phrase in my head: He who holds wages for all must not freeze to death in the snow.

In the evening, he sent out a special tweet thanking me and my group friend's mother.

Dr. Lin's tweet from the same day

That's what made me volunteer. We need good doctors like him.

I want to talk about the past.

When my child was 8 months old, he developed wheezing bronchitis, a persistent fever that kept him from drinking milk and sleeping.

All the other hospitals told me that the child was very serious and would be hospitalized with severe pneumonia. I didn't feel safe, so I went to Dr. Lin for advice.

He told me that I didn't have to go to the hospital and taught me how to use medicine and care at home until I was cured. He protected my child from overtreatment.

Later, I recommended a lot of people to see Dr. Lin, he will be patient and gentle explanation, teach them to correctly view the child sick this matter, do not blindly take medicine, to give the mothers the greatest support.

On January 27, the Western District of Union Hospital was transferred to a fever isolation hospital. Dr. Lin is firmly on the line.

But for lack of supplies, the hospital gave him an industrial protective suit, which did not meet the standards of medical protection.

He put it on and took a picture of himself, joking that he looked like a copy of iron man.

But I think he's more like a Baymax knockoff, because he's so warm.

This kind of industrial protective clothing worn by Dr. △ Lin can not be used as medical protective articles originally. It is mainly anti-corrosion, anti-static, anti-water mist / oil stain, anti-dust and heat insulation. Medical Protective clothing needs to be able to isolate bacteria, harmful ultra-fine dust, acid solution, etc. .

Mother Group of friends to see him like this, especially distressed, asked to give money together to buy the best doctor Lin medical protective clothing.

We have successfully purchased 200 Dupont 800 suits from the United States and intend to deliver them directly to their hospital.

Dupont 800, top-of-the-line security. Prices are going up because of the epidemic.

The cost of sending it home was paid for by a chinese-american man I didn't know.

We were struggling to find free shipping because it was so expensive. The eldest brother heard from a friend, patted his chest and said, this will send the most reliable logistics, guaranteed to the hands of the doctor. And paid $8,000 in shipping costs myself.

On January 31, I saw Dr. Lin for the second time. It was a clear day and the sun came out.

I told him, Hubei Mother Group Friends pet you, AH, for you to purchase dupont 800.

He froze, his eyes red with surprise. Then very embarrassed bowed his head to smile, said so high-grade protective clothing, have not worn it.

I laughed and said, go for it.

That day, I was on behalf of a group of Beijing friends, to give Dr. Lin a batch of goggles. The same batch of donated goggles was also distributed to 200 first-line departments at five other fever isolation hospitals.

I said, let me get a picture of you with your goggles.

He was so happy that he pulled down his mask and said that people would know it was me.

I crouched down during the shoot, saying it made him look taller. He was laughing so hard.

Holding the goggles donated by friends in Beijing, Dr. Lin smiled very cute

Dr. Lin's night shift is 8:00 p.m. to 8:00 a.m. , 12 hours.

"If I fall, what will happen to my wife, my children and my parents? " He said on his microblog? "

But then he said, "it's GonNa Happen, so fuck the damn virus like a man! "! ！! "

He turned and took a few steps, then suddenly turned and bowed
On January 30, a doctor in her mother's group said she had already returned to her hometown and was urgently told by the hospital to return to Wuhan for support.

"The only way to protect your family is to protect everyone. Every call comes back. "She said.

When we got to that point, I started crying.

Our conversations at the time

She also asked me for help because the hospital was short of supplies. I still had some goggles donated by my mother in Beijing.

They sent a bear doctor to get it from me.

It was a beautiful day, too. Around 3:00 p.m. , Dr. Bear arrived first. I felt so bad about missing half an hour because of something.

On my way out, I handed the baby to my grandmother and grabbed a bottle of vitamin water from the farmer's spring.

When I got downstairs, I saw him standing up straight, with a box-horse delivery boy standing beside him.

He was wearing a yellow and gray windbreaker and glasses, and he seemed a little out of it. Probably from exhaustion, too.

I tried to put my drink in his hand, and he kept waving, "No, keep it. ".

I said it's fine. He took it after all the work you guys did.

When I handed him 30 goggles, he kept saying thank you, thank you.

After turning around and taking a few steps, he suddenly turned around and bowed to me at a 90 degree angle. I waved my hand and said I couldn't do it.

Dr. Bear was a little excited and said, "thank you for your kindness. Let's cheer together. ".

In fact, I have experienced a lot of things over the years, has not shed tears for a long time. But this moment, I do not live up to the cry.

She's in respiratory intensive care, and the last N95's been running for a day and a night
At 8:30 p.m. on January 27, I learned that Dr. Liu of the Houhu district of Wuhan Central Hospital was in urgent need of a mask.

At that time, the central hospital has been adjusted to fever isolation hospital, Dr. Liu is head of the respiratory intensive care division, took over three wards, but only the last N95.

It's the only N95 she's had for a day and a night.

Another nurse friend of mine. After taking off the N95 mask, their faces will be left deep indentation.

I didn't have the N95 in my hand, so I immediately went to my mom's group for help. Luckily, a mom in the neighborhood just got a box of n95s. She asked me to give it to Dr. Lau for her.

At 9:00, I got my mask and called Dr. Lau. She was very touched, said so late, do not go, contact tomorrow.

The next afternoon, I walked to the Central Hospital.

It was so windy and cold. For more than 20 minutes, the wind cut my hands and ears like knives.

My phone wasn't working in the middle of it. After walking a long way, he met a couple and sought help.

There was a long, long line at the fever clinic that day, all the way to the side of the road. The crowd coughed.

[ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ][ dvnewspage ]

I made a conscious effort to walk around the block, away from the crowd, to the hospital entrance.

Dr. Liu was at the door to receive 600 goggles donated by netizens.

I handed her the mask and told her it was a gift from a mother in Wuhan. And then with her feeling about the vast network of friends.

Dr. Liu kept saying thank you, with gentle eyes.

I only have a good protection yourself, express my feelings at that time.

Dr. Lau received the mask

I think in times like these, especially when the life of an ordinary person is at stake, people need doctors even more than they need family members.

The last thing we want is for doctors to go down in the field, overspending themselves to meet our needs.

But there's no way around it.

They're still down
On January 24th, I learned from a good friend that Dr. Chow was "down. ".

She's a mutual friend. At the time, she had been under house arrest for a week with a new case of coronary pneumonia.

She was doing a C.T. on a potential patient. After working continuously for 36 hours, she began to develop symptoms of high fever, shortness of breath, and aching all over.

She was in a department that consisted of a plain surgical mask, no goggles, and a protective suit that everyone had to rotate after sterilizing.

It was her husband who got infected with her.

My friends cry at home every day, but all I can do is bring them some food.

Now that Dr. Zhou's husband has recovered, she hasn't.

The other "fallen" doctor is Li Hua. Is the Concord Wuhan Red Cross Hospital Infection Department in charge.

On January 25, a friend asked me for help, saying that Dr. Li Hua needed a mask urgently. By then, he had become infected and was sent to an isolation ward.

I only had 58 n90s I bought myself, and I gave them to him. And 100 surgical masks.

Those 58 n90s, he took after his colleagues to share a lot, he only kept 20, lasted 20 days.

It was another doctor, Chin, who came to get my mask for him. See Him that day, under the light rain, a trace of cold wind into the neck.

Dr. Chin came in a hazmat suit, covered from head to toe. Then go back to sterilize, no more, do not dare to take off.

After Dr. Chin took the mask, I took a picture of his back

Later, the cover story covered Li's experience as a Harvard man

Before he was infected, he treated more than 60 fever patients a day.

At first, however, Li and his colleagues did not have N95 masks or standard protective clothing.

They face patients wearing only two plain surgical masks and isolation clothing that can be washed and reused. And that level of protection is the highest in the entire hospital.

Since January 10, the number of fever patients coming to see the doctor has increased to more than 100 a day.

E.R. , respiratory, infection packed. On or around January 15, it was even more of a blowout.

In the emergency ward of the deputy director of the Department of Emergency Medicine, "there are patients lying on the bed and sleeping on the floor. "

Wuhan Xiehe Red Cross Hospital Isolation Ward

On the 22nd, Li Hua began to feel chest tightness and dizziness. But he thinks it's because he's been working so hard, and he's not taking it seriously. After the nurse gave him a bottle of glucose, he got up and went back to work.

On the 23rd, he had a CT scan, and the results surprised him. "The lung image showed a suspected new coronavirus infection. "! "

Dr Li Hua

On the 24th, Li Hua collapsed and was sent to an isolation ward.

During his stay, he also joined the hospital's telemedicine team, which provides video-conferencing services to patients online.

And I'm like, "please go back to work as soon as you get out. "

The only thing we can do in the face of this epidemic is to take it all on our shoulders. Even if no one else can.

Our Wuhan based writer, Fang Fang, recently wrote:

I used to say that a speck of dust from an era, falling on a person's head, is a mountain. When I said that, I didn't realize it. This time, it really impressed me. "

This experience, in my life, but also must be engraved on my heart.

I just hope these doctors are seen and remembered by more people.

AFTERWORD by Tian Jing:

Chenchen had been speaking to me in a somewhat hurried tone about the doctors. She's really worried about them.

Her volunteer work, it's actually kind of dangerous. Because they often come into direct contact with the doctors on the front lines. She has young children at home, too.

I asked her, are you afraid you might be infected, too?

She replied, "I haven't thought about it. "

"What I fear even more is that those who are infected will end up in despair because they can not be properly cared for, for fear that someone will give up their life. Afraid someone will go to extremes, take revenge on society, hurt innocent people. That's what worries me the most. "

Beautiful Chen Chen

The other day she said to me, "to be honest, I've had a bit of a breakdown. After reading the Internet about a suicide. You can feel the desperation, the powerlessness, on the screen. We're just lucky to be alive. "

I suggested that if she couldn't handle it, she might consider counseling. I hope she's okay.

In her body, I also saw some "bandit spirit" in Wuhan people. Outspoken, bold, bold.

There was a time in her circle of friends when she called herself an idealist
The Circle of Friends of △ Chen Chen

"Do not get used to the dark to justify the dark, do not gloat over your own meanness, do not mock those who are braver and more passionate than yourself. "

She thought she could do little, but it was also an insistence on idealism.

At present, Wuhan has tens of thousands of young volunteers in the front line of the epidemic.

We are all purely voluntary, organized in a wechat group, doing everything from organizing donations to saving pets left behind to helping city hotlines and sending medical staff to and from the hospital

In the walled city of Wuhan, they are also the most beautiful retrograde.

Hopefully, this time, they'll be remembered. The hope is that after this epidemic, people will be more kind to doctors and people to people.

What's GonNa Happen is GonNa Happen, and we're GONNA kill this damn virus. "

To all the mortals who have come forward. Peace be upon them.

AFTERWORD by Tian Jing:

Chenchen had been speaking to me in a somewhat hurried tone about the doctors. She's really worried about them.

Her volunteer work, it's actually kind of dangerous. Because they often come into direct contact with the doctors on the front lines. She has young children at home, too.

I asked her, are you afraid you might be infected, too?

She replied, "I haven't thought about it. "

"What I fear even more is that those who are infected will end up in despair because they can not be properly cared for, for fear that someone will give up their life. Afraid someone will go to extremes, take revenge on society, hurt innocent people. That's what worries me the most. "

Beautiful Chen Chen

In her body, I also saw some "bandit spirit" in Wuhan people. Outspoken, bold, bold.
